{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"297dd33c-ffa4-465e-b28d-2c302dd8b994","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool`.\n\n## Required `.csproj` changes\n\nAdd these properties to your `src/MyMcpServer/*.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n\n  <!-- The command users will run (e.g., `dotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer` then run `my-mcp-server`) -->\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata (required for nuget.org) -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n## Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack the tool\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n## Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server            # runs via stdio\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `PackAsTool` + `OutputType=Exe` are the critical properties\n- `ToolCommandName` controls the CLI command name (defaults to the assembly name if omitted)\n- Ensure your `Main` reads from stdin/writes to stdout for stdio transport\n- NuGet.org requires `PackageId`, `Version`, `Authors`, and `Description` at minimum","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"84ead6cd-3fad-4753-ac09-d50924a81e74","outputTokens":543,"requestId":"5033:867F7:DD0AED:FD4F83:69F2ABC7"},"id":"f6b99244-5157-45fe-ae7f-2a41a4702383","timestamp